### Basic Linux Commands

#### 1. File and Directory Management
These commands handle navigation, creation, deletion, and manipulation of files and directories.

**ls** - List directory contents.
- `ls`: Lists files in the current directory.
- `ls -l`: Lists files with detailed information like permissions and size.
- `ls -a`: Lists all files, including hidden ones.
- `ls /home`: Lists contents of the /home directory.
- `ls -lh`: Lists files with human-readable sizes.

**cd** - Change directory.
- `cd /etc`: Changes to the /etc directory.
- `cd ~`: Changes to the home directory.
- `cd ..`: Moves up one directory level.
- `cd`: Returns to the home directory (no arguments).
- `cd /var/log`: Changes to the /var/log directory.

**pwd** - Print working directory.
- `pwd`: Shows the current directory path.
- `pwd` (after cd /tmp): Outputs /tmp.
- `pwd` (in home): Outputs /home/username.
- `pwd` (in root): Outputs /.
- `pwd` (in /usr/bin): Outputs /usr/bin.

**mkdir** - Make directory.
- `mkdir newdir`: Creates a directory called newdir.
- `mkdir -p parent/child`: Creates nested directories.
- `mkdir dir1 dir2`: Creates multiple directories.
- `mkdir /tmp/test`: Creates test in /tmp.
- `mkdir -m 755 secure`: Creates directory with specific permissions.

**rmdir** - Remove empty directory.
- `rmdir empty`: Removes the empty directory.
- `rmdir dir1 dir2`: Removes multiple empty directories.
- `rmdir /tmp/test`: Removes test in /tmp if empty.
- `rmdir -p parent/child`: Removes nested empty directories.
- `rmdir olddir`: Removes olddir if it's empty.

**touch** - Create empty file or update timestamp.
- `touch file.txt`: Creates an empty file.
- `touch -t 202601010000 file`: Sets timestamp to Jan 1, 2026.
- `touch existing.txt`: Updates timestamp of existing file.
- `touch file1 file2`: Creates multiple files.
- `touch /tmp/log`: Creates log in /tmp.

**cp** - Copy files or directories.
- `cp file.txt copy.txt`: Copies file to copy.txt.
- `cp -r dir1 dir2`: Copies directory recursively.
- `cp file.txt /backup`: Copies to /backup directory.
- `cp -p file.txt copy`: Preserves permissions and timestamps.
- `cp *.txt docs/`: Copies all .txt files to docs/.

**mv** - Move or rename files/directories.
- `mv file.txt newname.txt`: Renames file.
- `mv file.txt /newdir`: Moves file to /newdir.
- `mv dir1 dir2`: Renames directory.
- `mv *.jpg images/`: Moves all .jpg to images/.
- `mv old.txt new.txt`: Renames old to new.

**rm** - Remove files or directories.
- `rm file.txt`: Deletes file.txt.
- `rm -r dir`: Deletes directory recursively.
- `rm -f force.txt`: Deletes without prompting.
- `rm *.tmp`: Deletes all .tmp files.
- `rm -i important.txt`: Prompts before deletion.

#### 2. Text Viewing and Editing
Commands for viewing, searching, and editing text files.

**cat** - Concatenate and display files.
- `cat file.txt`: Displays contents of file.txt.
- `cat file1.txt file2.txt`: Displays both files.
- `cat -n file.txt`: Displays with line numbers.
- `cat > newfile.txt`: Creates new file from input (Ctrl+D to end).
- `cat file.txt >> append.txt`: Appends to append.txt.

**more** - View file one screen at a time.
- `more longfile.txt`: Paginates longfile.txt.
- `more -d file.txt`: Paginates with prompts.
- `more /etc/passwd`: Views system file.
- `more file1 file2`: Views multiple files sequentially.
- `more +10 file.txt`: Starts from line 10.

**less** - Advanced pager for viewing files.
- `less file.txt`: Views file with navigation.
- `less -N file.txt`: Shows line numbers.
- `less /var/log/syslog`: Views log file.
- `less +/search file.txt`: Searches for "search" on load.
- `less file1 file2`: Views multiple files.

**head** - Display beginning of file.
- `head file.txt`: Shows first 10 lines.
- `head -n 5 file.txt`: Shows first 5 lines.
- `head -c 100 file.txt`: Shows first 100 bytes.
- `head /etc/hosts`: Shows top of hosts file.
- `head *.log`: Shows head of all .log files.

**tail** - Display end of file.
- `tail file.txt`: Shows last 10 lines.
- `tail -n 20 file.txt`: Shows last 20 lines.
- `tail -f log.txt`: Follows log in real-time.
- `tail -c 500 file.txt`: Shows last 500 bytes.
- `tail /var/log/auth.log`: Monitors auth log.

**nano** - Simple text editor.
- `nano file.txt`: Edits file.txt.
- `nano -w file.txt`: Edits without word wrap.
- `nano +10 file.txt`: Opens at line 10.
- `nano /etc/config`: Edits config file.
- `nano newfile.txt`: Creates and edits new file.

**vi** or **vim** - Advanced text editor.
- `vi file.txt`: Edits file.txt.
- `vi +/search file.txt`: Opens and searches for "search".
- `vi -r file.txt`: Recovers from crash.
- `vi /etc/hosts`: Edits hosts file.
- `vi newfile.txt`: Creates and edits new file.

**grep** - Search text using patterns.
- `grep "word" file.txt`: Searches for "word" in file.
- `grep -r "pattern" dir/`: Recursive search in dir.
- `grep -i "case" file.txt`: Case-insensitive search.
- `grep -v "exclude" file.txt`: Inverts match.
- `grep "^start" file.txt`: Matches lines starting with "start".

#### 3. System Information
Commands to get details about the system.

**uname** - System information.
- `uname -a`: All system info.
- `uname -r`: Kernel release.
- `uname -m`: Machine hardware name.
- `uname -s`: Kernel name.
- `uname -o`: Operating system.

**whoami** - Display current user.
- `whoami`: Shows username.
- `whoami` (as root): Outputs root.
- `whoami` (in script): Captures user in script.
- `whoami` (after su): Shows switched user.
- `whoami` (in terminal): Basic user check.

**df** - Disk space usage.
- `df -h`: Human-readable disk usage.
- `df /`: Usage of root filesystem.
- `df -T`: Shows filesystem types.
- `df -i`: Inode usage.
- `df /home`: Usage of /home.

**du** - Directory space usage.
- `du -sh /dir`: Summary in human-readable.
- `du -h /home`: Human-readable for /home.
- `du -c *.txt`: Total for .txt files.
- `du --max-depth=1`: One level deep.
- `du /var/log`: Usage of log dir.

**free** - Memory usage.
- `free -h`: Human-readable memory info.
- `free -m`: In megabytes.
- `free -s 5`: Updates every 5 seconds.
- `free -t`: Includes total line.
- `free -w`: Wide format.

**uptime** - System uptime.
- `uptime`: Shows uptime and load.
- `uptime -p`: Pretty format.
- `uptime -s`: System up since.
- `uptime` (in script): Monitors load.
- `uptime` (remote): Via SSH.

#### 4. Process Management
Commands to manage running processes.

**ps** - Process status.
- `ps aux`: All processes.
- `ps -ef`: Full format.
- `ps -u user`: Processes by user.
- `ps -p 1234`: Specific PID.
- `ps -o pid,cmd`: Custom output.

**top** - Interactive process viewer.
- `top`: Starts interactive mode.
- `top -u user`: Processes for user.
- `top -p 1234`: Monitor PID.
- `top -b -n 1`: Batch mode once.
- `top -d 2`: Delay 2 seconds.

**kill** - Terminate process.
- `kill 1234`: Kills PID 1234.
- `kill -9 5678`: Force kill.
- `kill -15 pid`: Graceful terminate.
- `kill -l`: List signals.
- `kill -SIGTERM pid`: Same as default.

**killall** - Kill processes by name.
- `killall firefox`: Kills all firefox.
- `killall -9 chrome`: Force kill.
- `killall -u user`: Kills user's processes.
- `killall -i name`: Interactive.
- `killall -r "pat*ern"`: Regex match.

**nice** - Run with modified priority.
- `nice -n 10 command`: Runs with niceness 10.
- `nice -5 highprio`: Negative for higher priority.
- `nice command`: Default +10.
- `nice -n 15 sleep 100`: Low priority.
- `nice -20 urgent`: Max priority (root only).

**renice** - Change priority of running process.
- `renice 10 -p 1234`: Sets niceness 10 for PID.
- `renice -5 -u user`: For all user's processes.
- `renice 0 -g group`: For group.
- `renice 15 5678`: Increases niceness.
- `renice -10 pid`: Decreases (higher priority).

#### 5. Permissions and Ownership
Manage file access rights.

**chmod** - Change file mode.
- `chmod 755 script.sh`: Executable by owner, readable by others.
- `chmod +x file`: Adds execute permission.
- `chmod -R 644 dir/`: Recursive.
- `chmod u+w file`: Write for user.
- `chmod 600 private.key`: Owner only read/write.

**chown** - Change owner.
- `chown user file`: Changes owner to user.
- `chown -R user:group dir/`: Recursive with group.
- `chown root file`: To root.
- `chown user: dir`: Owner and group.
- `chown -h user symlink`: For symlink.

**chgrp** - Change group.
- `chgrp group file`: Changes group.
- `chgrp -R group dir/`: Recursive.
- `chgrp staff project/`: To staff group.
- `chgrp -h group link`: For symlink.
- `chgrp users shared.txt`: To users.

#### 6. Networking
Commands for network configuration and diagnostics.

**ping** - Test network connectivity.
- `ping google.com`: Pings google.com.
- `ping -c 4 example.com`: 4 packets.
- `ping -i 2 host`: Interval 2 seconds.
- `ping 192.168.1.1`: IP address.
- `ping -s 100 host`: Packet size 100.

**ifconfig** or **ip addr** - Network interfaces (ifconfig deprecated; use ip).
- `ip addr show`: Shows interfaces.
- `ip addr show eth0`: Specific interface.
- `ip link set eth0 up`: Brings up.
- `ip route`: Shows routes.
- `ip addr add 192.168.1.100/24 dev eth0`: Adds IP.

**netstat** or **ss** - Network statistics (netstat deprecated; use ss).
- `ss -tuln`: TCP/UDP listening.
- `ss -p`: With processes.
- `ss -s`: Summary.
- `ss dst 192.168.1.1`: Destination filter.
- `ss -m`: Memory usage.

**wget** - Download files.
- `wget https://example.com/file`: Downloads file.
- `wget -O output.txt url`: Saves as output.txt.
- `wget -r site`: Recursive download.
- `wget -c url`: Continue interrupted.
- `wget --limit-rate=100k url`: Rate limit.

**curl** - Transfer data.
- `curl https://api.example.com`: Gets data.
- `curl -O file url`: Downloads.
- `curl -d "data" url`: POST data.
- `curl -I url`: Headers only.
- `curl -u user:pass url`: Basic auth.

**ssh** - Secure shell.
- `ssh user@host`: Connects to host.
- `ssh -p 2222 host`: Custom port.
- `ssh -i key.pem host`: Key auth.
- `ssh user@host command`: Runs remote command.
- `ssh -X host`: X11 forwarding.

#### 7. Package Management (Ubuntu/Debian-based)
Assuming APT for Debian-like systems.

**apt update** - Update package list.
- `sudo apt update`: Refreshes repositories.
- `sudo apt update -y`: Assumes yes.
- `sudo apt update` (with proxy): Uses env proxy.
- `sudo apt update --allow-releaseinfo-change`: Handles changes.
- `sudo apt update` (quiet): With -q.

**apt install** - Install package.
- `sudo apt install vim`: Installs vim.
- `sudo apt install -y package`: No prompt.
- `sudo apt install ./debfile.deb`: Local deb.
- `sudo apt install package=version`: Specific version.
- `sudo apt install --reinstall package`: Reinstall.

**apt remove** - Remove package.
- `sudo apt remove vim`: Removes vim.
- `sudo apt remove -y package`: No prompt.
- `sudo apt purge package`: Removes with config.
- `sudo apt autoremove`: Cleans unused.
- `sudo apt remove package1 package2`: Multiple.

**apt search** - Search packages.
- `apt search keyword`: Searches for keyword.
- `apt search ^vim`: Starts with vim.
- `apt search -n keyword`: Names only.
- `apt search keyword | grep desc`: Filters.
- `apt search installed`: No, use dpkg.

**dpkg** - Package manager.
- `dpkg -i debfile.deb`: Installs deb.
- `dpkg -r package`: Removes.
- `dpkg -l`: Lists installed.
- `dpkg -s package`: Status.
- `dpkg --purge package`: Purges.

#### 8. Archiving and Compression
Handle compressed files.

**tar** - Archive files.
- `tar -cvf archive.tar dir/`: Creates tar.
- `tar -xvf archive.tar`: Extracts.
- `tar -czvf archive.tgz dir/`: Gzip compress.
- `tar -xzvf archive.tgz`: Extract gzip.
- `tar -tvf archive.tar`: Lists contents.

**zip** - Compress to zip.
- `zip archive.zip file.txt`: Zips file.
- `zip -r archive.zip dir/`: Recursive.
- `zip -e archive.zip file`: Encrypted.
- `zip -d archive.zip file`: Delete from zip.
- `zip -T archive.zip`: Test integrity.

**unzip** - Extract zip.
- `unzip archive.zip`: Extracts.
- `unzip archive.zip -d dir/`: To dir.
- `unzip -l archive.zip`: Lists.
- `unzip -p archive.zip file`: Extracts to stdout.
- `unzip -o archive.zip`: Overwrites.

**gzip** - Compress files.
- `gzip file.txt`: Compresses to .gz.
- `gzip -d file.gz`: Decompresses.
- `gzip -9 file`: Max compression.
- `gzip -k file`: Keep original.
- `gzip -l file.gz`: Info.

**gunzip** - Decompress gzip.
- `gunzip file.gz`: Decompresses.
- `gunzip -k file.gz`: Keep gz.
- `gunzip -c file.gz > out`: To file.
- `gunzip -f file.gz`: Force.
- `gunzip *.gz`: All gz files.

#### 9. Advanced Text Processing
More powerful tools for text manipulation.

**sed** - Stream editor.
- `sed 's/old/new/' file`: Replaces first old with new.
- `sed 's/old/new/g' file`: Global replace.
- `sed -i 's/old/new/' file`: In-place.
- `sed '/pattern/d' file`: Deletes lines with pattern.
- `sed '1,5d' file`: Deletes first 5 lines.

**awk** - Pattern scanning and processing.
- `awk '{print $1}' file`: Prints first field.
- `awk -F: '{print $1}' /etc/passwd`: First field by :.
- `awk 'NR==5' file`: Prints line 5.
- `awk '{sum+=$1} END {print sum}' file`: Sums column.
- `awk '/pattern/ {print}' file`: Matches pattern.

**find** - Search for files.
- `find /dir -name "*.txt"`: Finds .txt in /dir.
- `find . -type f -size +10M`: Files >10M.
- `find / -user user`: Owned by user.
- `find . -mtime -7`: Modified last 7 days.
- `find . -exec rm {} \;`: Deletes found.

**xargs** - Build and execute commands.
- `find . -name "*.tmp" | xargs rm`: Deletes .tmp.
- `echo "1 2 3" | xargs echo`: Echoes args.
- `xargs -I {} mv {} new/ < list`: Moves from list.
- `find . | xargs grep "pattern"`: Searches.
- `xargs -p command`: Prompts.

**tee** - Read from stdin and write to stdout/files.
- `command | tee file.txt`: Writes to file and stdout.
- `ls | tee -a log.txt`: Appends.
- `echo "text" | tee file1 file2`: To multiple files.
- `command | tee /dev/null`: Discards but runs.
- `ps aux | tee proc.log`: Logs processes.

#### 10. System Administration (Advanced)
For system maintenance.

**sudo** - Execute as superuser.
- `sudo command`: Runs as root.
- `sudo -u user command`: As specific user.
- `sudo -i`: Root shell.
- `sudo -l`: Lists privileges.
- `sudo -s`: Shell as root.

**useradd** - Add user.
- `sudo useradd newuser`: Creates user.
- `sudo useradd -m user`: With home dir.
- `sudo useradd -G group user`: Adds to group.
- `sudo useradd -s /bin/bash user`: Shell.
- `sudo useradd -e 2026-12-31 user`: Expiry.

**passwd** - Change password.
- `passwd`: Changes own password.
- `sudo passwd user`: For user.
- `passwd -l user`: Locks.
- `passwd -u user`: Unlocks.
- `passwd -d user`: Deletes password.

**crontab** - Schedule jobs.
- `crontab -e`: Edits crontab.
- `crontab -l`: Lists.
- `crontab -r`: Removes.
- `crontab file`: Installs from file.
- `crontab -u user -e`: For user.

**systemctl** - Manage services (systemd).
- `sudo systemctl start service`: Starts.
- `sudo systemctl stop service`: Stops.
- `sudo systemctl status service`: Status.
- `sudo systemctl enable service`: Enables on boot.
- `sudo systemctl restart service`: Restarts.

**journalctl** - View logs (systemd).
- `journalctl`: Shows logs.
- `journalctl -u service`: For service.
- `journalctl -f`: Follow.
- `journalctl --since "2026-02-01"`: From date.
- `journalctl -p err`: Errors only.




This covers a progression from basic to advanced. You can copy this into a text file for reference. Practice in a safe environment like a virtual machine.

No, that's **not all** â€” Linux has hundreds (even thousands) of commands if you count every utility, but the list I gave earlier covers ~80â€“90% of what most beginners-to-intermediate users (and even many daily sysadmins/DevOps people) actually use regularly.

The previous list focused on the most universal and frequently needed commands. Below are the **most commonly recommended "next level" or missing commands** that appear again and again in 2025â€“2026 cheat sheets, DevOps/SRE guides, and sysadmin lists.

I'll group them into categories with **5 practical examples each** (just like before). You can copy-paste these to add to your text file.

### 11. Advanced File & Text Processing (very frequently used in real work)

**sort** â€” Sort lines of text files
- `sort file.txt` â†’ sorts alphabetically
- `sort -n numbers.txt` â†’ numeric sort
- `sort -r file.txt` â†’ reverse order
- `sort -k2 file.txt` â†’ sort by 2nd column
- `ls -l | sort -k5 -n` â†’ sort files by size numerically

**uniq** â€” Report or omit repeated lines (usually piped after sort)
- `sort file.txt | uniq` â†’ remove duplicates
- `sort file.txt | uniq -c` â†’ count occurrences
- `sort access.log | uniq -c | sort -nr` â†’ top IPs by count
- `cat file.txt | uniq -d` â†’ show only duplicated lines
- `history | cut -d' ' -f2- | sort | uniq -c | sort -nr` â†’ most used commands

**cut** â€” Remove sections from each line of files
- `cut -d: -f1 /etc/passwd` â†’ list usernames
- `cut -c1-10 file.txt` â†’ first 10 characters
- `ls -l | cut -d' ' -f9` â†’ list only filenames
- `cut -d, -f2,4 data.csv` â†’ columns 2 and 4
- `ps aux | cut -c1-80` â†’ truncate wide output

**tr** â€” Translate or delete characters
- `echo "Hello World" | tr 'a-z' 'A-Z'` â†’ uppercase
- `cat file.txt | tr -d ' \t'` â†’ remove spaces & tabs
- `echo "one,two,three" | tr ',' '\n'` â†’ comma to newline
- `cat file | tr -s ' '` â†’ squeeze multiple spaces
- `echo "file_name.txt" | tr '_' '-'` â†’ replace underscore

**wc** â€” Word, line, character, byte count
- `wc file.txt` â†’ lines, words, bytes
- `wc -l file.txt` â†’ only line count
- `find . -type f | wc -l` â†’ count files in directory
- `cat access.log | wc -l` â†’ count log entries
- `ls | wc -w` â†’ count items in directory

### 12. Disk & Filesystem (very important for troubleshooting)

**df** (you already have, but useful variants)
- `df -hT` â†’ human-readable + filesystem type
- `df -i` â†’ inode usage (very useful when "disk full" but df shows space)
- `df -h --total` â†’ add grand total

**du** (already have, good additions)
- `du -sh * | sort -hr` â†’ largest items in current dir
- `du -h --max-depth=1 /var | sort -hr` â†’ top-level usage in /var

**fdisk** / **lsblk** / **blkid** â€” disk partitioning & info
- `lsblk -f` â†’ list block devices + filesystem types
- `sudo fdisk -l` â†’ list all disks & partitions
- `blkid` â†’ show UUIDs and types of devices
- `lsblk -o NAME,SIZE,TYPE,MOUNTPOINT` â†’ clean device overview
- `sudo fdisk /dev/sdb` â†’ interactive partitioning (careful!)

**mount** / **umount**
- `mount` â†’ show mounted filesystems
- `sudo mount /dev/sda1 /mnt` â†’ mount partition
- `sudo umount /mnt` â†’ unmount
- `mount | grep /home` â†’ check specific mount
- `sudo mount -o remount,rw /` â†’ remount root read-write

### 13. Very Useful Everyday/DevOps Tools

**which** / **whereis** / **type**
- `which python3` â†’ full path to binary
- `whereis vim` â†’ binary + source + man pages
- `type ls` â†’ tell if alias, function, or binary
- `which -a python` â†’ all matching commands
- `type -a grep` â†’ show aliases + real command

**alias** (create shortcuts)
- `alias ll='ls -lah'` â†’ permanent in ~/.bashrc
- `alias update='sudo apt update && sudo apt upgrade -y'`
- `alias gs='git status'`
- `alias rm='rm -i'` â†’ safe delete
- `unalias ll` â†’ remove alias

**history** â€” command history
- `history` â†’ show last commands
- `history | grep apt` â†’ find apt commands
- `!123` â†’ repeat command number 123
- `history -c` â†’ clear history
- `export HISTIGNORE="ls*" ` â†’ ignore ls in history

**jobs** / **fg** / **bg** / **nohup**
- `jobs` â†’ list background jobs
- `sleep 100 &` then `fg` â†’ bring to foreground
- `nohup long-running-command > output.log 2>&1 &` â†’ run detached
- `bg` â†’ resume stopped job in background
- `kill %1` â†’ kill job number 1

### 14. Quick Troubleshooting Favorites (appear in almost every 2025â€“2026 DevOps list)

**dmesg** â€” kernel messages
- `dmesg | tail -20` â†’ last kernel messages
- `dmesg | grep -i error` â†’ error messages
- `dmesg --follow` â†’ live view
- `dmesg -T` â†’ human-readable timestamps
- `dmesg | grep usb` â†’ USB device issues

**lsof** â€” list open files
- `sudo lsof -i :80` â†’ what's using port 80
- `lsof /var/log/syslog` â†’ who has file open
- `lsof -p 1234` â†’ files open by PID
- `sudo lsof -u username` â†’ files by user
- `lsof +D /var/www` â†’ open files in directory

**strace** â€” trace system calls (advanced debugging)
- `strace ls` â†’ see what ls really does
- `strace -p 1234` â†’ attach to running process
- `strace -e open curl google.com` â†’ only file opens
- `strace -o trace.log command` â†’ save to file
- `strace -tt -T command` â†’ timestamps & duration

**htop** / **btop** (better than top â€” install if needed)
- `htop` â†’ colorful interactive process viewer
- `htop -u user` â†’ only one user
- `btop` â†’ modern alternative with graphs

### Final Thoughts
